  <static seed="576" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/ParabolaIntercepts80.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={x^{2}+4x+8}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,8\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\text{DNE}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}+4x+8}</m>, and we have <m>y=8</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,8)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}+4x+8}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {x^{2}+4x+8} \\
   0 \amp = {x^{2}+4x+8} \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The polynomial cannot be factored, so we use the Quadratic Formula to solve this equation.</p>
<p>Identify that <m>a=1,b=4,c=8</m>. We have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   x \amp = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a} \\
   x \amp = \frac{-(4) \pm \sqrt{(4)^{2}-4(1)(8)}}{2(1)} \\
   x \amp = \frac{-4 \pm \sqrt{-16}}{2} \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The square root of a negative number us <alert>not real</alert>, so this quadratic equation has no real solution.</p>
<p>The parabola doesn<rsq/>t have any <m>x</m>-intercept. Type <c>DNE</c> (does not exist) as the solution.</p>
</solution>
